{meta: artist Red Sovine}
{meta: writer Jack Rhodes and John Fitzmorris}

{start_of_verse: Verse 1}
[G]There's a rose vine clinging [D7]tightly by my [G]window
[D7]I placed it there when first our love was [G]new
[C]And as our [G]love began to grow the [D7]rose vine flourished [G]too
[C]The symbol of [G]a love so [D7]sweet and [G]true
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 2}
[D7]Then one day you promised we'd be [G]married
[D7]A big red rose appeared upon the [G]vine
[C]The splendor and the [G]glory of our [D7]love began to [G]shine
[C]The rose vine seemed to [G]know you'd [D7]soon be [G]mine
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 3}
[D7]Then came the day the rose began to [G]wither
[D7]It seemed to know before one word was [G]said
[C]You'd lose your love for [G]me and marry [D7]someone else [G]instead
[C]The rose fell off the [G]rose vine [D7]soon was [G]dead
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 4}
[D7]Oh withered rose vine clinging there so [G]lonely
[D7]So like a memory that don't want to [G]die
[C]I feel your thorns deep in [G]my heart with [D7]pain so hard to [G]hide
[C]Oh rose of love oh [G]rose of love [G][D7]goodbye
{end_of_verse}
